<HEADLINE>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="4"> FT 16 NOV 92 / Junior social security minister attends serivce at Westminister Cathedral</s>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="5"> Ann Widdecombe, a junior social security minister and a leading opponent of the ordination of women in the Church of England, yesterday attended a service at the Roman Catholic Westminister Cathedral in London.</s>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="6"> Yesterday's Sunday services were the first since the vote by the general synod of the Church of England in favour of allowing the ordination of women.</s>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="7"> Miss Widdecombe has left the Church of England and said many other people were in the same 'self-imposed excommunication'.</s>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="8"> She added: 'Today I come as a visitor from nowhere'.</s>

<s docid="FT924-7590" num="9"> Dr George Carey, archbishop of Canterbury, said on BBC Radio that he would be amazed if many people left the church because of the vote.</s>
</TEXT>
